04547nam a22006735i 9780520390102DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203901027 a10.1525/97805203901022doi  a(DE-B1597)627900  a(OCoLC)1343250983  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aN8243.S576bB43 2022 7aART0151002bisacsh04a704.9/49306362223/eng/202205171 aBeach, Caitlin Meehye, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSculpture at the Ends of Slavery /cCaitlin Meehye Beach. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Phillips Collection Book Prize Series ;v900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. “Within a Few Steps of the Spot”: Art in an Age of Racial Capitalism -- t1. Grasping Images: Antislavery and the Sculptural -- t2. “The Mute Language of the Marble”: Slavery and Hiram Powers’s The Greek Slave -- t3. Sentiment, Manufactured: John Bell and the Abolitionist Image under Empire -- t4. Relief Work: Edmonia Lewis and the Poetics of Plaster -- t5. Between Liberty and Emancipation: Francesco Pezzicar’s The Abolition of Slavery -- tCoda. “Sculptured Dream of Liberty” -- tNotes -- tList of Illustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom abolitionist medallions to statues of bondspeople bearing broken chains, sculpture gave visual and material form to narratives about the end of slavery in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. Sculpture at the Ends of Slavery sheds light on the complex—and at times contradictory—place of such works as they moved through a world contoured both by the devastating economy of enslavement and by international abolitionist campaigns. By examining matters of making, circulation, display, and reception, Caitlin Meehye Beach argues that sculpture stood as a highly visible but deeply unstable site from which to interrogate the politics of slavery. With focus on works by Josiah Wedgwood, Hiram Powers, Edmonia Lewis, John Bell, and Francesco Pezzicar, Beach uncovers both the radical possibilities and the conflicting limitations of art in the pursuit of justice in racial capitalism's wake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntislavery movements. 0aArt, Moderny19th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aSculpturexThemes, motives. 0aSculpture, AmericanxThemes, motives. 0aSlavery in art. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520390102?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520390102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520390102/original  a978-3-11-076649-3  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099281-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2022  aZDB-23-DPKb2022